  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Frameworks and Conventions\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Provide standardized approaches and principles\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering\n- Sharing of financial intelligence\n- Extradition agreements\n- Cross-border legal cooperation\n\n3. Regulatory Compliance Standards\n- Harmonized Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Suspicious transaction reporting protocols\n- Uniform anti-money laundering (AML) standards\n- Risk assessment guidelines\n\n4. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- International sanctions\n- Asset freezing\n- Criminal prosecution coordination\n- Bilateral and multilateral enforcement agreements\n\n5. Information Sharing Networks\n- Interpol financial crime databases\n- Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units\n- Global information exchange platforms\n\n6. Technical Assistance and Capacity Building\n- Training programs\n- Best practices development\n- Supporting developing countries' legal frameworks\n\nThese intersections create a comprehensive approach to combating money laundering globally.",
